Title: Ramy Youssef: Feelings (2019) | Why Do They Make Her Wear That (Clip) | HBO
Name: Jasmine S
Comment:
I come from a Muslim family and no it's not all coming from free choice. And it's also not always by force. All humanity faces the internal pressure to fit in and follow society's ideals norms and moral mapping. I would question how much of people's choices are coming from their own idividuality or from a notion in their head of who they are and what is right or wrong.

 I believe we all have choice at the end of the day but  I wonder how much choice a woman in oppressive or even just conservative environments actually has. I wouldn't say she has completely free choice when some choices are not as safe, accepted, and I would say dangerous at times for example to wear what you want if what you want is not to cover up. 

So in semi conservative environments maybe nobody is forcing her to wear those things directly but she's backed into a corner and it can feel safer and more moral in the corner than out and after a while the corner becomes normal and familiar even to the women themselves.

Comment:
I was in Iran six weeks ago. I became friends with two girls down in Shiraz, and went on two dates with a girl up in Tehran (who I'm still in contact with). One of the two girls in Shiraz got a fine for not wearing the hijab in her husband's car. I can't remember what the amount was but it was substantial. 
The girl in Tehran is currently trying to flee the country but she can't leave without her husband's (whom she's trying to divorce, hence me being on the date with her) or father's permission. 
All three girls hate wearing the hijab, and it's very much forced upon them. It's not culture, it's not choice, it's oppression. Khomeini enforced it in the aftermath of the Islamic Revolution. 
Stop. Making. Excuses. For. It. 
It's in no way akin to a woman in the west wearing a short skirt and stilettos because of cultural norms - it is enforced with violence and prison and fines. If you put a hoodie on over your dress you don't get western morality police bundling you into the back of a fucking van. 
This neglect and disregard amongst western liberals for women in certain middle eastern countries is infuriating, and it's all driven by the desire to show how inclusive and open minded we are, when it actually portrays the opposite.

Exactly whose confidence and whose trust has been betrayed, who has murdered whom, and which commandment of which supposedly just law has been broken here. If you ask me she is not exactly the paragon of virtue, truth and beauty herself. But I still feel this in no way exonerates or absolves O J Simpson of his guilt or excuses his unmanly and cowardly behavior and downright deplorable conduct.  He should have chosen to be the better gentleman and the larger individual and simply let her go, and let her have her will and let her have her say and let her have her way. It is neither good nor just, nor right for one to impose ones will or for one to impose ones way upon another, no matter whether the relationship is based or not based on blood, although I am not speaking for someone or putting it past someone who would rather be a boss and a dictator and a tyrant.   No court of law recognizes if not the validity, certainly not the sanctity of a marriage, where one or both parties are engaged in an adulterous extra-marital relationship, and a breach of trust is a far graver offense than a breach of contract. Candidly the reason I do no like to read much or pay attention to the news too much is because much of what I read and hear and see deeply upsets, worries, disturbs and alarms me and hurts me, makes me question and doubt my faith both in the sovereignty of god and in the splendor of man.

A few things to note:

1 This isn't how gun purchases work, you don't need a lease (atleast on a federal level). 
2 Bump stock are now currently illegal. 
3 all you typically need is a valid form of ID, ability to fill out form 4473 (includes all personal and residential info, and background questionnaire) and pass a NICS background check. Lastly, some states have mandatory waiting periods. 
4 Nobody calls their go to FFL their "arms dealer."
5 Shotguns are for Fudds. Or scythes according to a certain tv company remaking Looney Tunes.

Title: How Bert Kreischer Got His Guns Without The Paperwork | Netflix Is A Joke
Name: Butch Lane
Comment:
It is fascinating that Americans have such a BIG attraction to guns. Though given the current president, so many others, and the statements they make, the attraction appears to be, like so much else Americans prioritize, a feeling of control or power. Very rarely, if ever, does the need for protection or safety strike as a true priority. 
Most often, the same ones who claim to be "fighting for their rights," also appear to ignore those same rights of others. 
Typical of the American stereotype, they want what they want but it must be how they want it, with little to no thought for others. 
In America, "thoughts & prayers" are the BIG reaction following a shooting. In countries like Canada or New Zealand, where shootings are an anomaly, the government actually governs, and gun control means actual control. And, as even small children are taught, if you're not going to play with your toys responsibly and reasonably, they'll be taken away. It's fairly basic. 
After mass shootings, Canada and New Zealand didn't pussyfoot around and hedge on the possibility of maybe doing something. There was no claim to respect a schedule of death, as Republicans claim to follow after. 
In Canada and New Zealand, immediately, within two weeks, after a mass shooting, both countries banned assault-type weapons. It should also be noted, neither country offers politicians or lobbyists huge amounts of cash to maintain or pursue an idea. Gun ownership in Canada is also not the required priority to one's identity, like in the US. Though still very popular, especially in rural parts of the country, somehow Canadian gun owners have figured out a way to prioritize. Compromising is not a term the 

United States looks to understand well. It's all or nothing. 
As Canadians know, gun owners can be law-abiding citizens, and most gun owners understand that assault-weapons serve no beneficial civilian purpose. Assault-style weapons are designed for one purpose and one purpose only — to kill the largest amount of people in the shortest amount of time (think LasVegas), no one needs an AR-15 to bring down a deer.

Title: George Lopez Addresses the Police and ICE | Netflix Is A Joke
Name: Jack Secret
Comment: I remember when George Lopez was one of the funniest comedians around.  His bits about Latino culture were hilarious & accurate.  It wasn't mean-spirited and it wasn't infused with political BS to get cheap applause like he is now.   If you're Latino, married to a Latino or live in a city heavily populated with Latinos, you couldn't help but laugh and easily relate to him.  For those of you interested, try and find his first CD called Alien Nation.  It will have you laughing in tears.  His second CD Right Now, Right Now was excellent too.    Today's George Lopez is a sad shadow of what he once was. He's lazy, self-absorbed and polarizing.  Because I enjoyed his humor so much in the past, I always tune in to see if he's turned a corned and gotten back to his roots.  Unfortunately, its just more of the same drivel and low hanging fruit.

Title: How Hannah Gadsby's High-Functioning Autism Works | Netflix Is A Joke
Name: Rachael Manto
Comment: Oh, this is stirring up old memories. I used to always do poorly in primary school activities that required an understanding of common knowledge. For instance, most people would reply “orange” if asked the colour of a carrot. But I liked to look though vegetable seed catalogues for fun as a child, so I knew that carrots can also be purple, red, yellow, and white. So I would consistently give “wrong” answers because my brain struggles to weigh information according to social use. When asked by an adult and I would explain my reasoning, they would get exasperated and say not to show off and to just put the normal answer. But I couldn’t ever seem to figure out what the defaults were. My brain couldn’t say “hmm. We have seen many colours of carrots and have grown purple ones in the veggie patch. But on cartoons, in my classmates’ lunches, etc carrots are only ever drawn as orange. So I should use that colour as my default when communicating the idea of carrots”.

Title: How Hannah Gadsby's High-Functioning Autism Works | Netflix Is A Joke
Name: Stephanie's Musings
Comment:
Whenever I am teaching a concept that a student doesn’t understand, I try to explain it in a different way. 

And if a child says something absurd, I try to figure out their line of thinking. Or I ask them what made them think of such a thing. It’s often very funny, and in many ways “logical” from the child’s point of view.

Title: How Hannah Gadsby's High-Functioning Autism Works | Netflix Is A Joke
Name: Toxiphilia
Comment:
I remember when I was 10, about a year before I got my autism diagnosis, my class were gonna send letters to this kid's show called Hjärnkontoret (=The Brain Office, aka a program about science and stuff). Everyone got to send in their own question so I wanted to know what the lil black part of the pencil was.

Now, to understand this, you need to know this: in Swedish, that good ol' pencil that usually have an eraser in the butt is called a blyertspenna and the bly-part of it means lead. So when we were all reading our questions out loud, everyone started to laugh. The teacher giggled, from what I remember. Some of the boys shouted "it's made out of lead" and I felt like the biggest idiot on the planet, shrinking even further into my lil shell. It definitely didn't help me get over my constant fear of giving a wrong answer, so this incredibly shy, quiet child became even more shy and quiet.

Today I know that the lil black part of the pencil is made out of graphite and that it contains no lead. Idk why I wanted to tell this story but I did and thus I did. Have a lovely day.

Name: YuyuLeBrave
Comment:
Reminds me of that time when I was 4. I was yelling at the back of the car for reasons history decided to forget. But yelling with dedication nonetheless. My mom, a school teacher, trained in the arts of screaming children, was out of options, and threatened to abandon me next to a field.
 Alas, I was not one for understanding the concept of threats, and knew she wouldn't do that. 
So I kept screaming. 
My tired, out of options, mom wanting to be taken seriously, stopped the car next to a Field.
 I learned later in life, taking care of 4 years old myself, that this is usually the limit of the bluff that works, and the child calms down.
But I didn't do that.
My mother, now committed, took me out of the car, and put me next to the field. No objection from me. Not wanting to back down, she got back in the car and LEFT saying "I'll come back when you're calm".
She came back a minute or two later, estimating that I would be taking her seriously enough to be quiet for the last 5 minutes of the car ride. She got out out of the car. I stared at her straight in the face and said "I'm not calm yet". 

She put me back in the car and I SCREAMED for the rest of the car ride, the end. 

BONUS : My seven year old sister, contrarely to me, was very impressed at my mom and was crying "please don't abandon my sister" and that's why my mom had to come back quicker than she wanted.

This is a mood. I ended up turning a lot of teachers against me through sheer cluelessness. But my daughter came out with one of my favorites.

So the teacher in her 4th grade class read them a story about the 3 little pigs in which, in a twist ending, the third pig ATE THE WOLF. My daughter went up to the desk after and quietly asked her whether in doing so the third pig had therefore eaten his own brothers. Some teachers break more quietly I guess because the teacher just asked her to sit back down.

I think most of us can agree that this was actually a very logical question given the usual pacing of the story and I wonder that the author missed that little hiccup.

I`ve  have had these comments all my adult life. Also, `Are you OK? you look really angry.`
 This conversation sometimes took place in nightclubs:
 Random stranger: `Cheer up mate,  it might never happen` . 
 Me:                          ` Too late mate, it`s already happened. I have terminal cancer`. 
RS:                             `Oh fuck, sorry mate`.
 Even worse for me was when people tried to get me to dance. Sometimes they would even violate my personal space and literally attempt to drag me on to the dance floor.
I don`t dance. Never have, never will. I don`t get it; it`s something that on the few occasions I had a go, I felt clumsy and exposed. I much preferred to just sit and watch people`s behaviour, which I have always found fascinating.
 A bit like being at the zoo, only with no bars between me and the inmates.
Other than that I quite liked those places. It meant I didn`t have to engage in small talk, what with the volume and all, which was fine by me.

Name: Cucumamacacapipi
Comment: I'm a man and I've had people tell me to smile a handful of times. So I don't think it is just something men say to women, I think it's just something people say occasionally. But it was extremely irritating every time it happened. Because it's someone trying to tell you what to do. AND they are telling you to do something good, so now you have to choose not to smile in order to establish valid autonomy. AND they get annoyed if you respond telling them you will smile when u have a good reason too, so I think women/feminists do have a point that it's probably ppl with subconscious alterior motives who are telling others to smile. Unless you're just saying it in general, to try and be uplifting. Also, I am not a woman but I am extremely short, only about 5 feet tall, and I have a youthful face, so a lot of white people think I'm a minor.  So they may be saying it thinking that they're not talking to an adult man but a teen, who it generally would be more acceptable to mentor randomly in passing.

Title: Jerry Seinfeld Compares Married Men To Game Show Losers | Netflix Is A Joke
Name: jav retama
Comment:
Gotta say I've never been a big fan of Seinfeld's stand up...the funniest for me are his interviews and conversations with other funny people like in CICGC for his wit and being so articulate with life lessons, advice, or life observations sprinkled in that are not part of his comedy persona.

Having said that...I can clearly see the evolution of his standup and humor in this special. I think this is his funniest  stand up special yet. He talks about his family (he rarely did before)  mixed in with his observational humor. It is also raised up to another level by his physical comedy, expressions, and mimicry...

I can't help, but to see a bit of Tom Papa's humor run off from his family and Sebastian Maniscalco's physicality...these influences just bring out the best in Seinfeld that has not been seen before. 

I highly recommended it...and that is saying something from a "stand up non-fan".

Actually, quail are pretty cool.  I happened upon a mother quail and her brood once, and she did "the fake broken wing act".  Fascinating to watch.  The mother hobbles around while the young one quickly run out of the way and hide under a bush.  The mother tempts the predator by hopping around like she's injured, making sure to always lead the predator away from the young ones.  How she does the calculations, I don't know, but she's always careful to never flail around in a way that looks like she's headed to where the babies are.
On the other hand, if restaurants are serving quail eggs, then either some of these mother quail are no bloody good at their job, or else they simply decided that parenthood , or at least having more than 2.5 kids, was simply not for them.

Title: Kevin Hart's House Got Robbed | Netflix Is A Joke
Name: xevious2501
Comment: They say success is the root of failure especially for comics, becuase success kills hunger and drive.  Quite understandable, if you consider winning as the end of the race.  After that hard push to be the victor, you begin to power down, slow to a trot and take a breather. you bask in the spoils of victory and loose that flame that enabled you to win in the first place.   Thats how it is for most people and their careers of choice,  But for entertainers, the ones doing it correctly,  they keep themselves from crossing that finish line.  ever moving it away from themselves the more and more they get close to it.  As a result they remain in form, remain sharp, and though seldom ever viewed as the best of the best because they refuse to cross that finish line,  their performance typically far exceeds their competition.   Kevin Hart clearly is not at the level he was years ago.  it is to be expected,  as he's been at the top for a very long time,  but he's crossed that finish line several times.  and every time he's been a bit less and less of what he was in the past.   Now.. at least in this show,  he's become more of a cliche to his own act.  and all that success has stagnated his growth.    Dave Chappelle on the other hand, not only moves that finish line far from him, but he's also deliberately taken himself out the race just so he can get back into training to remake himself,  And unlike kevin, who as been the same exact kevin throughout his comedic career,  Dave has worn many different faces, been several distinctively different sorta of comics, exploring many ways and angles  of comedy to reach that finish line first only to hit the reset button and do it all over again.   Dave is a monster, because his comedy is that of fine wine,  the older he gets, the more his comedy digs intellectually deep.  Kevin hart is a great comedian, but dave chappelle is one of THE GREATS.  And all of the greats pay tribute to one who's comedic and intellectual prowess transcends generations and that lenny bruce.  Our most beloved comedians those who have hit hard have nothing on Lenny Bruce, especially when taking into account his act, and his era.   He was way WAY ahead of his time.  As for K hart..  i think he needs to hit the reset button and take it back to the beginning.  He's forgotten his goal,  not by measure of fame and wealth, but by will to succeed.

Title: Marc Maron Thinks Marvel Movies Are The Next Big Religion | Netflix Is A Joke
Name: Ed Smythee
Comment:
(2:48) It's weird that he's shitting on the superhero genre when he's clearly familiar with pieces of terminology that are associated with mainstream superhero comics (i.e., "titles").

I know that he's had indie/underground comic artists like Peter Bagge and Tony Millionaire on the podcast, but generally speaking, the term "title" isn't used in reference to the type of small press or self-published comix that those guys produce. You'd usually use that word to denote an ongoing series involving mainstream characters at a company like Marvel or DC.

Regardless, even though I disagree with Maron on this point, I can respect his opinion and I think the bit is well-executed.

Her description of “white women” is very much rich white women, and not at all “most white women” like she says. Most working class white women, Irish immigrants, Polish immigrants, Italian immigrants, and Appalachian mountain women, they all had to work too, either in the fields or in the factory, on top of doing most if not all of the domestic work. These liberals going on about “white women” as if they were all rich need to chill the fuck out. Still, the criticisms Michelle makes still stand for middle class and upper class white women... just not “most white women.” Since we’re talking about the Titanic, let’s not forget the Irish mother singing her children to sleep so they don’t have to be awake while they drown to death because the ship security won’t let them off the ship. THAT is representative of most white women throughout history, not Becky from Bel Air, and we’d do well to remember it.

Title: "Russians" |  Russell Peters - Almost Famous
Name: D K-sky
Comment:
The "backwards" sounding Russian has an explanation:
Most of the words in English end with vowels, so the flow of speech is almost uninterrupted, like a song. One word stacks with another like a jigsaw puzzle. It starts abruptly but then they drag the word.
Russian on the other hand has majority of the words ending with consonants, so speaking Russian is like jumping on the river rocks, one by one. (I'm native russian speaker) We drag our words and then end them abruptly.
So it's basically English in reverse.

Title: "Russians" |  Russell Peters - Almost Famous
Name: rougewillow
Comment:
Well, in Russia there are two different naratives for native Russian and Russian cityzent -  native Russian is the one who is called RUSSKY, wile Russian cityzent is called ROSSIANIN. And the reason for this is that like America, Russia is very multicultural, so not all people living IN Russia are actually native Russians. They ARE however Russian cityzents. Some cityzents really imbody the culture of native Russians ( its called being Russian at heart ) Others don't - they speak good russian, but their culture, religion and the way they interact with other people is VERY VERY different to any other native Russians or othere native groups of Russian Federation. This goes particulary for muslims and buddist living on the Easter and Southern side of Russia. 


Its a tricky subject to adres, and many foreigners don't seems to care anyway, so regardless of the backround many Russian cityzents call themselfs Russians "automaticly".  But by that they refer to themselfs as ROSSIANE - a proud narative most Russians LOVE using.


I'm sure it feels like too much information, but there is no shorter way to explane it. 


P.S. most of the times, guys with names such as Khabib ect. are from Caucasian Mountain region, like Chechnya, Dagistan, Osetia or region of Tatarstan. Their skin color is also darker.

Title: Black Music Tells You Everything You Need to Know - Roy Wood Jr.
Name: Micah Atkins
Comment:
See, I prefer comedy that involves a noticeable amount of thought into jokes.  You can't try to convince me that there's an out of control problem with minority groups and their inability to take a good joke, when a natural part of that existence is to be on the receiving end of greater society's bullsh*t . You'd  have to be resilient, as well as uniquely thick skinned, which could reach an inevitable limit. Even if they'd come to that point, ...it's still be inappropriate to suggest that these were cases of oversensitivity by people who've lost the American abilty to take a joke. 

Roy just did a 6 minute set that was specifically touching on a politically divisive topic, yet found a way to be funny for anyone listening. That was intentional. Just a professional being successful at his craft.

We all can remember back in school, how there were a very select number of students, who seemed to have only one talent throughout their entire time in grade schools.  These fools had a knack for getting large groups of students to laugh at one (or two) defenseless classmate. Admittedly, the guy (or girl) has a way of making , otherwise nice kids, giggle even when they're annoyed by the everyday antics of the class clown.  Well, it shouldn't surprise you to know that most comedians will confess to having this gift of gab back in school. Some used it to ward off bullies.

Point is, they should be far past that level of comedy if they are truly meant to be in that profession.  Mny of us are funny motherf*ck*rs who can just look at everyday people and come up with something to crack on.  That's not a gift & like many things in life, we lose the urge to maturity.

Well, there seems to be a powerful push by comedians (and those of the far right) to normalize unfiltered offensiveness to the point of being celebrated.
I'm not that easy, nor should anyone else be......

Just a thought.
